Note in the output of str() that data type (here either chr or num). R has six data types:

numeric: numbers like 1 and 16.823 (sometimes also called double). logical: true/false values (boolean): either TRUE or FALSE. character: text, e.g.a, Hello! Im Ada. and name@domain.com. integer: integer numbers, denoted in R by the letter L: 1L, 55L. complex: complex numbers, like 2+3i. raw: used to hold raw bytes.

You will probably only need to think about the top three.

If you have missing data (which show as NA), some functions will show an NA, e.g.

mean(msleep$sleep_rem)
## [1] NA

Can ignore NAs with the na.rm = TRUE argument

mean(msleep$sleep_rem, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 1.87541

Changing types

Factors: Say you have a study with two groups, group 1 and group 2. The labels 1 and 2 are just labels, they could just as easily be group A and group B or group experimental and control.

We need to tell R that these are categorical and not numerical. This is important because say for example you have 3 groups, 1,2 and 3, theres no way in which group 1 + group 2 = group 3. It also doesnt make sense to say that someone in group 3 is twice as far from someone in group 1 as someone in group 2. We can tell R this by making the variable a factor, with the as.factor() function.

group <- c(1,1,2,1,2,1,2,2,1)

class(group)
## [1] "numeric"
group <- as.factor(group)

class(group)
## [1] "factor"

Using %>% pipes

Within the tidyverse is a set of tools called pipes. These are operators that improve your codes readability and structure the code in such a way that you read the functions in the order that they are applied instead of inside out. E.g

new_variable <- function_2(function_1(data))

becomes

new_variable <- data %>% function_1 %>% function_2

For example:

height <- c(160, 163, 170, 172,175, 178, 180, 182, 185, 190, 191, 190, 166)

mean(log(height))
## [1] 5.174955
height %>%
  log %>%
  mean
## [1] 5.174955

Modifying a variable

Say we want to change the sleep_total column to be in minutes instead of hours. For this we can use the mutate function

msleep$sleep_total
##  [1] 12.1 17.0 14.4 14.9  4.0 14.4  8.7  7.0 10.1  3.0  5.3  9.4 10.0 12.5 10.3
## [16]  8.3  9.1 17.4  5.3 18.0  3.9 19.7  2.9  3.1 10.1 10.9 14.9 12.5  9.8  1.9
## [31]  2.7  6.2  6.3  8.0  9.5  3.3 19.4 10.1 14.2 14.3 12.8 12.5 19.9 14.6 11.0
## [46]  7.7 14.5  8.4  3.8  9.7 15.8 10.4 13.5  9.4 10.3 11.0 11.5 13.7  3.5  5.6
## [61] 11.1 18.1  5.4 13.0  8.7  9.6  8.4 11.3 10.6 16.6 13.8 15.9 12.8  9.1  8.6
## [76] 15.8  4.4 15.6  8.9  5.2  6.3 12.5  9.8
msleep <- msleep %>%
  mutate(sleep_total = sleep_total*60)

Say we have a reversed item on a scale

example_data <- example_data %>%
  mutate(item_2R = 7 - item_2R,
         item_4R = 7 - item_4R)

Create a new variables

The mutate function also allows the creation of a new variable.

Say we want to create a column showing the ratio of brain weight to body weight:

msleep <- msleep %>%
  mutate(brain_body_ratio = 100*brainwt/bodywt)

Recoding variables

Say we have gender coded as 0 and 1, we might want to recode this explicitly as male and female for clarity. Or say we have items in a scale that have responses such as Not at all, Very much that we want to recode as numeric:

example_data %>%
  mutate(item_5 = recode(item_5,
                         "Extremely dissatisfied" = 1,
                         "Very dissatisfied" = 2,
                         "Somewhat dissatisfied" = 3,
                         "Somewhat satisfied" = 4,
                         "Very satisfied" = 5,
                         "Extremely satisfied" = 6))
##    subject item_1 item_2R item_3 item_4R item_5
## 1        1      6       6      2       6      3
## 2        2      4       4      2       1      3
## 3        3      5       2      5       6      3
## 4        4      3       5      4       3      2
## 5        5      3       2      2       5      1
## 6        6      6       2      3       4      2
## 7        7      4       4      6       6      5
## 8        8      5       3      2       2      1
## 9        9      5       3      3       5      3
## 10      10      2       1      3       5      3
example_data <- example_data %>%
  mutate(item_5 = recode(item_5,
                         `1` = "Extremely dissatisfied",
                         `2` = "Very dissatisfied",
                         `3` = "Somewhat dissatisfied",
                         `4` = "Somewhat satisfied",
                         `5` = "Very satisfied",
                         `6` = "Extremely satisfied"))

Grouped summaries

Commonly we want to compute a function for each value of a variable. Lets look at the airquality dataset:

library(data.table)
## 
## Attaching package: 'data.table'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     between, first, last
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     transpose
?airquality
## starting httpd help server ...
##  done
aq <- data.table(airquality)

What if we want to compare how a particular variable varies over the months - it would make sense to look at key summary values e.g.the mean and standard deviation for each month separately. This is how to do this using tidyverse:

aq %>%
  group_by(Month) %>%
  summarise(meanTemp = mean(Temp))
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   Month meanTemp
##   <int>    <dbl>
## 1     5     65.5
## 2     6     79.1
## 3     7     83.9
## 4     8     84.0
## 5     9     76.9

If we have NA values there, we can use na.rm = TRUE argument:

aq %>%
  group_by(Month) %>%
  summarise(meanOzone = mean(Ozone))
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   Month meanOzone
##   <int>     <dbl>
## 1     5        NA
## 2     6        NA
## 3     7        NA
## 4     8        NA
## 5     9        NA
aq %>%
  group_by(Month) %>%
  summarise(meanOzone = mean(Ozone, 
                             na.rm = TRUE))
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   Month meanOzone
##   <int>     <dbl>
## 1     5      23.6
## 2     6      29.4
## 3     7      59.1
## 4     8      60.0
## 5     9      31.4

We can compute summary statistics that use multiple variables, or multiple summary statistics at once:

aq %>%
  group_by(Month) %>%
  summarise(meanTemp = mean(Temp),
            correlation = cor(Temp, Wind))
## # A tibble: 5 x 3
##   Month meanTemp correlation
##   <int>    <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1     5     65.5      -0.373
## 2     6     79.1      -0.121
## 3     7     83.9      -0.305
## 4     8     84.0      -0.508
## 5     9     76.9      -0.570

We can also summarise across many variables that share a property, for example say we want to create means for all numeric variables:

aq %>%
  group_by(Month) %>%
  summarise(across(
    where(is.numeric),
    mean, na.rm = TRUE
  ))
## # A tibble: 5 x 6
##   Month Ozone Solar.R  Wind  Temp   Day
##   <int> <dbl>   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1     5  23.6    181. 11.6   65.5  16  
## 2     6  29.4    190. 10.3   79.1  15.5
## 3     7  59.1    216.  8.94  83.9  16  
## 4     8  60.0    172.  8.79  84.0  16  
## 5     9  31.4    167. 10.2   76.9  15.5

We can also simply count how many occurences there are of a particular variable using n():

aq %>%
  group_by(Month) %>%
  summarise(days = n())
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   Month  days
##   <int> <int>
## 1     5    31
## 2     6    30
## 3     7    31
## 4     8    31
## 5     9    30

and the number of distinct occurences of a variable using n_distinct():

aq %>% summarise(months = 
  n_distinct(Month))
##   months
## 1      5

Filling in missing values

Sometimes we might want to fill in some missing values with the previous non-missing value. First lets put in some missing data in our dataset:

aq$Month[c(2:3, 36:39, 70)] <- NA

# Some values of Month are now missing:
head(aq)
##    Ozone Solar.R Wind Temp Month Day
## 1:    41     190  7.4   67     5   1
## 2:    36     118  8.0   72    NA   2
## 3:    12     149 12.6   74    NA   3
## 4:    18     313 11.5   62     5   4
## 5:    NA      NA 14.3   56     5   5
## 6:    28      NA 14.9   66     5   6

Lets fill in the gaps:

aq %>% 
  fill(Month) ->

aq %>% fill(Month) %>%

       summarise(days = n())

Merging data from multiple sources

It might be the case that for one project we have data from multiple sources that we want to combine into one data frame. For example,

rev_data <- read.csv("data/sales-rev.csv", sep = ";")
weather_data <- read.csv("data/sales-weather.csv", sep = ";")

str(weather_data)

If you are lucky and the rows or columns match each other_exactly_ you can use bind to connect the two dataframes.

Lets first extract three subsets of these dataframes: the revenue for January, the revenue for February and the weather for January:

rev_data %>% filter(between(DATE,
            as.Date("2020-01-01"),
            as.Date("2020-01-31"))
                    ) -> rev_jan

rev_data %>% filter(between(DATE,
            as.Date("2020-02-01"),
            as.Date("2020-02-29"))
                    ) -> rev_feb

weather_data %>% filter(between(
            DATE,
            as.Date("2020-01-01"),
            as.Date("2020-01-31"))
                 ) -> weather_jan

We can see the rows of rev_jan and weather_jan correspond exactly, which means we can bind the columns together. Similarly, rev_jan and rev_feb have identical columns, so we could bind their rows together. Lets see:

Unfortunately it will often be the case that the rows and columns dont match exactly and we want to use a common identifier present in each dataset to specify which rows/columns we want to be matched together. There are different possibilities for how to do this. First we identify the variable that is in common between the datasets that we wish to use to connect the two. This is called a key. In this example, well use DATE as our key.

  • Inner join: If we want to only keep the rows that have a date that appears in both datasets. Any rows that have a DATE that only appears in one will be dropped.
  • Outer join: If we want to keep all rows from both datasets, even if the DATE only appears in one of the dataframes.

Basic Data Plotting

We will use the ggplot2 package, which is already loaded when we load tidyverse so we dont have to load it separately. The syntax can look a bit confusing and unintuitive at first, and there are sometimes (depending on what kind of plot you want) simpler alternatives that are fine if you are just trying to get an overview of your data. But for reports where you want to have more flexibility for content, style and layout, ggplot can really come in handy.

Theres no single right or wrong way to make plots, it really depends on what you want to create and balancing that with the simplicity/complexity of the code. Well go through some examples and then its really up to you how you implement it yourself.

Scatter plot

Lets start with a basic scatterplot using the msleep data, plotting total sleep against REM sleep time:

For a basic scatter plot:

data(msleep)
plot(msleep$sleep_total, msleep$sleep_rem)

ggplot:

ggplot(msleep, aes(x = sleep_total,
                   y = sleep_rem)) +
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

We need three components:

  • the data set (here, msleep)
  • the aesthetics (the x axis, y axis)
  • geoms (what do we want to plot, e.g.geom_point for a scatter plot)

So your ggplot function will always have the structure of

ggplot(data, aes) + geom

Simple style tips

Personally Im not a fan of the grey background, we can change this by adding a theme, e.g.theme_bw()

ggplot(msleep, aes(x = sleep_total,
                   y = sleep_rem)) +
  geom_point() + 
  theme_bw()
## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

We can change the axis labels and title like so:

ggplot(msleep, aes(x = sleep_total,
                   y = sleep_rem)) +
  geom_point() + 
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "Total sleep time",
       y = "REM sleep time",
       title = "Total vs REM Sleep Time")
## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

We can plot different colors for different groups by adding a color argument to the aesthetic:

ggplot(msleep, aes(x = sleep_total,
                   y = sleep_rem,
                   color = vore)) +
  geom_point() + 
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "Total sleep time",
       y = "REM sleep time",
       title = "Total vs REM Sleep Time")
## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Lets create a plot to see how animals brain weight is related to their body weight:

ggplot(msleep, aes(brainwt, bodywt, colour = vore)) + 
      geom_point() +
      xlab("Brain weight") +
      ylab("Total sleep time") +
  theme_bw()
## Warning: Removed 27 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

We have a couple of outliers that are making the overall pattern difficult to interpret. We can address this by changing the x-axis and y-axis limits (although be aware that we are now excluding some data points from the plot):

ggplot(msleep, aes(brainwt, bodywt, colour = vore)) + 
      geom_point() +
      xlab("Brain weight") +
      ylab("Total sleep time") +
  theme_bw() +  
  xlim(0, 2) +
  ylim(0, 1000)
## Warning: Removed 29 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

We can use facet_wrap to create a separate plot for different groups:

ggplot(msleep, aes(x = sleep_total,
                   y = sleep_rem)) +
  geom_point() + 
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "Total sleep time",
       y = "REM sleep time",
       title = "Total vs REM Sleep Time") +
  facet_wrap(~vore)
## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Boxplots

We can do this using base R or ggplot:

boxplot(sleep_total ~ vore, data = msleep)

ggplot(msleep, 
       aes(vore, sleep_total)) +
      geom_boxplot()

Histograms

# Base R:
hist(msleep$sleep_total)

# ggplot2:
ggplot(msleep, aes(sleep_total)) +
      geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Bar charts

# Base R
barplot(table(msleep$vore))

# ggplot2
ggplot(msleep, aes(vore)) +
      geom_bar()

Saving plots

We can assign a plot we make to a variable name, e.g.myPlot:

myPlot <- ggplot(msleep, aes(sleep_total, sleep_rem)) +
      geom_point()

We can then see this just by calling the variable name:

myPlot
## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

and add things later:

myPlot + labs(title = "My Plot")
## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

and finally save it:

ggsave("myplot.pdf", myPlot, width = 5, height = 5)
## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
